website_summaries.verdict: A top-notch racquet that's used by one of the best players in the world, Mohamed Elshorbagy.
pros: A great choice for advanced players, it comes in a choice of weights to suit a variety of game styles
Power and balance helps players hit the target with good handling and shot control
cons: Can be tough to handle well
Beginners may find it shows up too many flaws in their game

customer_reviews.title: this is a racquet best fit for an advanced player
customer_reviews.text: Wish I read the reviews carefully before buying it: this is a racquet best fit for an advanced player. I am a beginner, and immediately noticed all the flaws in my game--it is really hard to generate power with this racquet unless your swing is very good. It is really frustrating to have such a great tool and not be able to use it properly. I would not recommend buying it unless you really know what you doing in squash.
customer_reviews.author: Leonid Libenzon

customer_reviews.title: Strings not as advertised.
customer_reviews.text: Not as described. Description clearly states strung with x-biphase. This racquet arrived strung with technifibre synthetic gut. I would not have purchased this racquet had I known about the different strings. The synthetic gut is a cheaper string, thus the value of this racquet was inflated.
customer_reviews.author: Bleubook

customer_reviews.title: Immediate improvement in shot power and control
customer_reviews.text: I've been playing squash for over 30 years now. I've used squash racquets from a bunch of different recognized brands: Head, Prince, BlackNight, Wilson, etc., all in the price range of $90 ~ $120. Just recently and for the first time I got a Tecnifibre CarboFlex 125 racquet and I have to say that I am impressed. From the very first time I tried it I could immediately feel more shot power combined with more control. With this racquet I am hitting my targets more accurately and much more often. I've also hit the walls hard a couple of times during my games and the frame is still intact. I have no problem giving this racquet a 5 star.
customer_reviews.author: FERNANDO BOLANOS

customer_reviews.title: Strings broke after 5 uses
customer_reviews.text: The frame is great, but the strings broke after just a handful of games. The person who re-strung it was amazed at the cheapness of the strings...ended up costing me $35 to put new ones on.
customer_reviews.author: AdeM

customer_reviews.title: Strength shots
customer_reviews.text: I have a Head Nano 110, which I love, and bought the Tecnofibre to try something more powerful. The first one is more for beginners and the Tecnofibre is a little more heavy but strength shots... you really can fell the difference.
customer_reviews.author: Catia Reg

customer_reviews.title: This racket also has a sweet spot if you connect well enough with the ball ...
customer_reviews.text: I also own a Head CT135, this racket produces a little less power in your strokes compared to the Head. However, i prefer this racket due to the increased ability to attack the ball i.e. play volleys etc. This racket also has a sweet spot if you connect well enough with the ball it can be quite explosive. There is also minor vibrations upon connecting with the ball more than the Head CT 135 at least but not enough for it to be a major concern in my opinion.
customer_reviews.author: Amazon Customer

customer_reviews.title: Nice racket with enough power and control
customer_reviews.text: I am playing ~2 times a week with this racket for almost two years now and its serving me really well. This racket is lightweight (125g) with a little head-heavy nature. Both the racket and factory string is sturdy enough (I didn't have to change the string yet). Would recommend for everyone!
customer_reviews.author: A H M Mahfuzur Rahman

customer_reviews.title: Five Stars
customer_reviews.text: First time I splurged on a squash racquet but I can definitely see the difference. Very pleasant to use.

customer_reviews.title: Great racquet.
customer_reviews.text: I’ve only had this racquet for about six weeks, so I can’t be certain in the durability. But the racquet is light weight. I like it very much. I’ll report back on durability as I continue to use it.

customer_reviews.title: A lethal weapon with a downside
customer_reviews.text: While this racquet is a lethal weapon if in good hands, strings are not that great. My string broke within a month of buying and I didn't even use it for 'heavy-duty' shots. I ended up paying 40 bucks for re-stringing it, and now I have to remind myself evey time to play tight ball shots cautiously.
customer_reviews.author: mayank

customer_reviews.title: Strings came off after using the racket 3 times
customer_reviews.text: The racket is of good quality. But the springs broke after my 3rd use and I did not even hit a wall with it. Went to a repair shop in Manhattan, NY and the guy knew what happened right away. He said that this happens all the time with this brand and I had to pay 40$ for new stringing.

customer_reviews.title: Five Stars
customer_reviews.text: Great product, fast delivery, much faster than expected. Tremendous stick to upgrade an attacking type of game. Previously used Head Ct115 to force myself into generating my own power through racquet head swing rather than its weight. Immediately felt the improvement on the Carboflex 125 and is so maneuverable and powerful that I can get out of tough defensive situations and switch to offense with not much effort. It is also a beautiful looking stick.

customer_reviews.text: Great balance for volleying. Sweet spot has tremendous power, but the sweet spot is smaller than most racquets. Definitely more suited for skilled player. My other racquets are Black Knight C2C NXS Black which is about 9 grams heavier, but still balanced and lot more power.
